best cookie ever. i use all butter, but make sure they are cold before putting in oven, and bake for less time. i put dough back in fridge after rolling each tray. double recipe at minimum.

Rating: 4
Hallelujah!! You have rescued my favorite cookie recipe! It was the darn Crisco! This has been a treasured cookie recipe until about 5 years ago, when suddenly the recipe stopped working. I could not figure out what had changed. It resulted in hard crispy cookies that spread A LOT, in spite of following the recipe to a T. When I read some reader comments that Crisco had been reformulated about that time, I went out and bought hydrogenated, bad-for-you, grocery store brand shortening and tried a batch. Now THAT'S the chewy cookie I used to love! Thanks so much for helping me solve this mystery. For those of you trying this recipe for the first time, be sure you do not use shortening that is "0 transfat."

Rating: 4
I have made these dozens of times. They are known in my circle of friends simply as "The Best Cookie Ever." It is not uncommon when looking forward to an event for a friend to ask "Are you bringing The Best Cookies Ever?" or to overhear at an event. "Have you tried these ginger cookies, yet? They're the best cookies ever." I generally triple the recipe because they go so fast (and a quadruple won't fit in the KitchenAid). I usually add a little extra candied ginger (about an extra quarter cup per recipe). Recently, I had some leftover lemon filling from Glittering Lemon Sandwich Cookies and used the filling to make lemon ginger sandwich cookies. That was a delightful twist. I'll probably try that again.

Rating: 4
I started making these two Christmases ago, and while I always like to make new, untried baked goods every holiday season, these are the ones that I consistently receive requests for. They're easy and quick and absolutely delicious -- crispy outside, chewy inside. I bake them when I go to holiday parties, or to give to neighbors, and I have yet to meet anyone who doesn't want the recipe from me afterward. I haven't had trouble with the puffiness or crispiness, like some other people...but I use crisco from a tub and not a stick, for whatever that's worth, and follow the recipe exactly. I've only ever modified to add a bit more crystallized ginger. Protip: The Ginger People sell crystallized ginger chunks, and they are almost juicy, and have the best flavor of any I've tried. I always use those when I can get them!

Rating: 4
Fantastic ginger cookies, I've started making these every Christmas. Everybody loves these. After some experimenting, here's how I get them to rise as pictured: I let the dough rest about 6 hours, if not overnight. After rolling, I chill a tray of them in the freezer for 2 minutes, right before I put them in the oven - perfect puffed up cookies every time (even after they cool)!

