I had never made a ginger cookie before, but my husband loves them, so I decided to give it a try. Instead of trying the basic recipe, I combined a few changes which had been suggested by previous reviews and WOW - what a fabulous spicy/substantial cookie I got! Here's what I changed: 1)used 2t ground ginger + 1t grated fresh ginger, 2)used 1C crystallized ginger, 3)used 3/4C butter-no shortening and 4)added a few turns of fresh ground black pepper and 1/4t cayenne - FABULOUS!!! Everyone who tried them loved them and they were gone in a flash! Perfect texture and looked just like the picture, but get ready, they've got a bite!

Rating: 3
I do a lot of baking, though not cookies very often. I thought these cookies very easy to make, and very much worth making. Very delicious! Do allow time for the dough to rest, and leave plenty of room between cookies on the baking sheet. Great with a cup of tea or cocoa. I made the recipe as written, they surprisingly did look just like the picture, but I didn't get a yield of 30 cookies, just about 25. Perhaps I made them too large. If you're not sure of the timing, just look for the cracking on the top, and err on the side of under- vs over-baking. For the added ginger flavor I had in the freezer "ginger chips" sold by the King Arthur Baking Co. I don't know if these are technically crystallized ginger or not, but they definitely added flavor and texture without being hard like a nut. Next time I might try the black pepper, more butter vs shortening, and/or orange zest enhancements. Great cookie!

