Clarification: substitute 1/2 cup butter for the shortening, and drop the additional 1/4 cup of butter.

Rating: 4
I make these for gatherings, and they routinely get rave reviews. I made some changes to the basic receipe. The first was to simply eliminate the shortening - the cookies bake up softer. Second, I halved the amount of cloves called for, as I found the clove taste overpowering the other flavors. Third, I always use the darkest brown sugar available - Muscovado or Billingtons Molasses sugar. Finally, rolling them in turbinado sugar before baking gives them a bit of crunch to go with the soft cookie.

Rating: 3
Before you jump all over me for rating a recipe I changed, I did the rating for two reasons. First, these are really delicious (the description of 3 forks), secondly, it appears that this "new and improved" website calculates all comments as negatives, so when someone simply makes a statement, and doesn't rate, it says 0% would make again! I don't want to skew the numbers badly on this one. That said, I substituted applesauce for the shortening, used light brown sugar, and used 1 cup unbleached all purpose flour, 3/4 cup whole wheat, and 1/4 cup soy flour. I was generous with the chopped (coarsly) crystallized ginger as well. For all you in the Milwaukee area, Outpost Food Coop carries it in their bulk section, and it is wonderful. I will definitely repeat these, with the same substitutions. They taste like something from the neighborhood coffee shop!

