These cookies are chewy on the inside and crispy exterior. I omitted the salt, a good move, as the molasses and spice is quite savoury and the saltwould have pushed it over the top. Using organic hard wheat flour the yield excellent - 3 dozen cookies. Next time I will add lemon zest for a little kick.

Rating: 4
Fantastic recipe--I've made them about 15 times since the Bon Appetite issue published. Sometimes I leave out the crystallized ginger--my wife doesn't like it. They come out great either way. The best thing about these cookies is that they aren't too sweet. As a result I can eat many in one sitting. I even make this recipe in spring and summer because I get requests for it from friends and family.

Rating: 3
With the addition of 2 tbsps of grated fresh ginger, these cookies were divine. I made them for a bake sale. My favourite customer was the woman who came by, bought two, then returned two minutes later to buy another 16! I'll reduce the sugar by about 1/4 cup next time, but the recipe is definitely a winner.

Rating: 4
We just did a ginger cookie competition at work and this recipe won by a long shot. Forget about any other ginger cookie recipes - this one is the best.

Rating: 4
These are great--crispy sweet coating surrounding a chewy, fragrant cookie with the spicy surprise of that awesome crystallized ginger. Wow. I will make them again and again. Do not leave out anything or substitute anything.

Rating: 3
I made these cookies for a cookie exchange at work - they didn't win first place, but they were darn close. I gave up on the search for crystallized ginger and used actual grated ginger root -- it made for some strange stringy bits in the cookies, but the taste was beyond compare!

Rating: 3
I had a hard time finding ground cloves and made the recipe without it, the cookies still turned out great. I'll be making this for friends this Holiday season. P.S. I got my crystallized ginger from Trader Joe's. It comes in a bag for less than $4 and is enough for around 3 recipes.

Rating: 4
Great holiday cookie! After reading the reviews, I omitted the ground cloves and crystallized ginger since I didn't have any, and the cookies still turned out delicious. I also put the cookies in the refigerator for about 10 minutes before baking. Will definitely add this to my annual holiday cookies list.

Rating: 4
Just made these and they won't last till Christmas! The best ginger cookies I've ever had! HINTS: Crystalized ginger "chips" can be found at the King Arthur Flour website. Also refrigerate the dough for an hour before forming balls using a cookie scoop -- no sticky mess and the cookies were perfect to roll in the sugar.

Rating: 3
These came out great. Two suggestions: I decreased the amount of crystallized ginger to about 1/4 - 1/3 cup. Still had the zippy flavor of the ginger. The ginger is a pain to chop - I tried my Cuisinart adn a small hand-held chopper. Nothing works as best as a very sharp knife and patience. Keep the dough refrigerated at all times. 10 minutes baking time (in my oven) was plenty. Excellent recipe. I'd make it again.

Rating: 4
I made these cookies the other day and they turned out fantastic! I did omit the crystalized ginger because I had trouble finding it. The only recommendation I have is to refigerate the cookies on the cookie sheets for about 10 minutes before baking them. It makes them crack more on top while baking and look a whole lot nicer.

Rating: 3
the crystalized ginger is hard to deal with, very sticky. the cookies turned out really yummy though.

Rating: 4
Made a vegan version of these cookies that turned out superb both flavor-wise and texture. Used flax seed boiled in water for egg replacement. Used Sunsweet Lighter Bake for shortening + butter replacement. Had to add more molasses because the ratio with the replacements didn't work out, but the cookies were wonderful.

Rating: 4
Just recently, I called my mother-in-law to get her old family recipe for molasses sugar cookies. Well I lost the recipe (after I made them), and so I was so happy that this recipe is almost identical. The only thing different is that the old one does not call for the crystalized ginger, so I used only the ground kind. FANTASTIC! These cookies are superb!!!

Rating: 4
These are THE BEST ginger molasses cookies, and I consider myself a fanatic of that genre. I've tried probably dozens of recipes, and this is the absolute best. These will be the ones I make again and again.

Rating: 4
I doubled the recipe and found that it needed an extra 1/2 c. of flour when doubling. These are the best cookies! Everyone I serve these to wants the recipe. I made 2" balls for some of the cookies, which made the wonderful giant size cookies. I also rolled them in turbinado sugar which added a nice touch. Don't leave out the crystalized ginger; it is what elevates these to a level above other ginger cookies.

