My favourite cookies growing up were very similar to these without the crystallized ginger. This addition makes them perfect.

Rating: 4
Best molasses/ginger cookies I have ever tasted. Crystallized ginger adds a lot--so does the sugar coating on the outside. It's buried at the end of the recipe...but you do need to refrigerate for an hour--so give yourself time. Took these with two other cookies (chocolate toffee and chocolate chunk, orange and hazelnut--much more glamourous choices) to a dinner party, they all came in a first place tie. Great with a late harvest riesling dessert wine. Would also like to try them with apples and cheddar (in the fall).

Rating: 4
Not perfect, but good enough to have made 4 batches in the last month. Has motivated me to find a new supplier for Crystallized Ginger... (Great American Spice - $4.95/lb.) Love the ginger kick. If you have study enough food processor, I "pulsed" the ginger to a mince. A little sticky and chopped too fine, but much quicker.

Rating: 3
I omitted the crystallized ginger and still found these to be very good cookies.

Rating: 3
Although the batch I made were not as "puffy" as the ones shown in the magazine, these were absolutely delicious! I wish I could think of a quick way to chop all that crystallized ginger, but it was well worth the time (maybe 10-15 minutes) as it is an integral part to the crunchy-chewy part of this cookie.

Rating: 4
These are the best version of ginger snap cookies that I have ever made. They were perfectly crisp on the outside and chewy on the inside. The crystallized ginger is a must and really gives these cookies a spicy kick. It also makes alot of cookies , so you'll have enough to share!